### Interfaces

Interfaces define the shape of an object — the names and types of its properties.

### Basic Interface

```typescript
interface User {
  name: string;
  age: number;
  email: string;
}

function greet(user: User): string {
  return `Hello, ${user.name}!`;
}

const alice: User = {
  name: "Alice",
  age: 30,
  email: "alice@example.com"
};
```

### Readonly Properties

```typescript
interface Config {
  readonly apiKey: string;
  readonly endpoint: string;
}

const config: Config = {
  apiKey: "abc123",
  endpoint: "https://api.example.com"
};
// config.apiKey = "new"; // Error: readonly
```

### Optional Properties

```typescript
interface User {
  name: string;
  age?: number; // Optional
  email?: string; // Optional
}
```

### Index Signatures

```typescript
interface StringDictionary {
  [key: string]: string;
}

const dict: StringDictionary = {
  hello: "world",
  foo: "bar"
};
```

### Excess Property Checks

TypeScript checks for unexpected properties:

```typescript
interface Point {
  x: number;
  y: number;
}

// Error: 'z' does not exist in type 'Point'
// const p: Point = { x: 1, y: 2, z: 3 };
```

> **Key Point:** Interfaces can be merged (declaration merging) and extended.

